# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-components
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-components/api-customevent] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-components/api-customevent] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:web-components/api-customevent] The **`CustomEvent`** interface can be used to attach custom data to an event generated by an application.
[src:web-components/api-customevent] As an alternative to `CustomEvent`, you can subclass the `Event` interface to add custom data and behavior.
[src:web-components/api-customevent] Returns any data passed when initializing the event.
[src:web-components/api-customevent] If the event has already been dispatched, this method does nothing.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] The **`CustomElementRegistry`** interface provides methods for registering custom elements and querying registered elements.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] To get an instance of it, use the `window.customElements` property.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] To create a scoped registry, use the `CustomElementRegistry()` constructor.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] Creates a new `CustomElementRegistry` object, for scoped usage.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] Returns the constructor for the named custom element, or `undefined` if the custom element is not defined.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] Returns the name for the already-defined custom element, or `null` if the custom element is not defined.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] Upgrades a custom element directly, even before it is connected to its shadow root.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] Associates a scoped registry with a DOM subtree, setting the custom element registry on each inclusive descendant and upgrading any custom elements.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] Returns an empty `Promise` that resolves when a custom element becomes defined with the given name.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] If such a custom element is already defined, the returned promise is immediately fulfilled.
[src:web-components/customelementregistry] See the Examples section in our guide to using custom elements.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] The **`<slot>`** HTML element is a placeholder inside a Web Component that you can fill with your own markup when the component is used.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] This lets you create separate DOM trees and present them together.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] Slots can contain plain text, other HTML elements, or other web components.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] A slot can also contain default content, which is displayed if the slot is not assigned other content when the web component is used.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] This element includes the global attributes.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] A *named slot* is a `<slot>` element with a `name` attribute, while an *unnamed slot* has no `name` attribute, and the name defaults to the empty string.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] When a shadow root uses named slot assignment, top-level child elements of its host are rendered in slots that have a matching name in their `slot` attribute.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] Slot names should be unique per shadow root: if you have two slots with the same name, all of the elements with a matching `slot` attribute are rendered in the *first* slot.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] All top-level child elements that don't have a `slot` attribute are rendered in the first unnamed `<slot>` element, which is referred to as the *default slot*.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] The `name` has no effect if the shadow root uses manual slot assignment.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] For more information see `shadowrootslotassignment` on the `<template>` element and `Element.attachShadow()`.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] This HTML shows how a number of named slots might be declared within a `<template>` element.
[src:web-components/elements-slot] Note that these slots are only used as slots when the template is used inside a shadow root.
[src:web-components/htmltemplateelement] It’s been available across browsers since November 2015.
[src:web-components/htmltemplateelement] The **`HTMLTemplateElement`** interface enables access to the contents of an HTML `<template>` element.
[src:web-components/htmltemplateelement] A read-only `DocumentFragment` which contains the DOM subtree representing the `<template>` element's template contents.
[src:web-components/htmltemplateelement] A string that reflects the value of the `shadowrootmode` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:web-components/htmltemplateelement] A boolean that reflects the value of the `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:web-components/htmltemplateelement] A boolean that reflects the value of the `shadowrootclonable` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:web-components/htmltemplateelement] A string that reflects the value of the `shadowrootcustomelementregistry` attribute of the associated `<template>` element, indicating that the declarative shadow root will use a scoped `CustomElementRegistry`.
[src:web-components/htmltemplateelement] A boolean that reflects the value of the `shadowrootserializable` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:web-components/htmltemplateelement] A string that reflects the value of the `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute of the associated `<template>` element.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] One of the key features of web components is the ability to create *custom elements*: that is, HTML elements whose behavior is defined by the web developer, that extend the set of elements available in the browser.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] This article introduces custom elements, and walks through some examples.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] A custom element is implemented as a class which extends `HTMLElement` (in the case of autonomous elements) or the interface you want to customize (in the case of customized built-in elements).
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] This class will not be called by you, but will be called by the browser.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Immediately after defining the class, you should register the custom element, so you can create instances of it using standard DOM practices, such as writing the element in HTML markup, calling `document.createElement()`, etc.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] In the class constructor, you can set up initial state and default values, register event listeners and perhaps create a shadow root.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] At this point, you should not inspect the element's attributes or children, or add new attributes or children.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] See Requirements for custom element constructors and reactions for the complete set of requirements.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Once your custom element is registered, the browser will call certain methods of your class when code in the page interacts with your custom element in certain ways.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] By providing an implementation of these methods, which the specification calls *lifecycle callbacks*, you can run code in response to these events.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The position of a custom element in the DOM can be manipulated just like any regular HTML element, but there are lifecycle side-effects to consider.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Each time a custom element is moved (via methods such as `Element.moveBefore()` or `Node.insertBefore()`), the `disconnectedCallback()` and `connectedCallback()` lifecycle callbacks are fired, because the element is disconnected from and reconnected to the DOM.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] However, since these callbacks are typically used to implement any required initialization or cleanup code to run at the start or end of the element's lifecycle, running them when the element is moved (rather than removed or inserted) may cause problems with its state.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] You might for example remove some stored data that the element still needs.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] If you want to preserve the element's state, you can do so by defining a `connectedMoveCallback()` lifecycle callback inside the element class, and then using the `Element.moveBefore()` method to move the element (instead of similar methods such as `Node.insertBefore()`).
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] This causes the `connectedMoveCallback()` to run instead of `connectedCallback()` and `disconnectedCallback()`.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] To make a custom element available in a page, call the `define()` method of `Window.customElements`.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] This must start with a lowercase letter, contain a hyphen, and satisfy certain other rules listed in the specification's definition of a valid name.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The custom element's constructor function.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Only included for customized built-in elements, this is an object containing a single property `extends`, which is a string naming the built-in element to extend.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Once you've defined and registered a custom element, you can use it in your code.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The examples above register custom elements on the global `CustomElementRegistry` accessed via `Window.customElements`.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] This means every custom element name you register must be globally unique across the entire page.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] As applications grow and begin combining components from multiple libraries, global name collisions can become a problem — if two libraries both try to define `<my-button>`, one of them will fail.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] One way to use a scoped registry is to pass it to `Element.attachShadow()` via the `customElementRegistry` option.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] You can also associate a scoped registry after the shadow root has been created by calling `initialize()`.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] For declarative shadow DOM, you can use the `shadowrootcustomelementregistry` attribute on a `<template>` element.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Like built-in elements, custom elements can use HTML attributes to configure the element's behavior.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] To use attributes effectively, an element has to be able to respond to changes in an attribute's value.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The `attributeChangedCallback()` callback is then called whenever an attribute whose name is listed in the element's `observedAttributes` property is added, modified, removed, or replaced.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Note that if the element's HTML declaration includes an observed attribute, then `attributeChangedCallback()` will be called after the attribute is initialized, when the element's declaration is parsed for the first time.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] For a complete example showing the use of `attributeChangedCallback()`, see Lifecycle callbacks in this page.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Built in HTML elements can have different *states*, such as "hover", "disabled", and "read only".
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Some of these states can be set as attributes using HTML or JavaScript, while others are internal, and cannot.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Whether external or internal, commonly these states have corresponding CSS pseudo-classes that can be used to select and style the element when it is in a particular state.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Autonomous custom elements (but not elements based on built-in elements) also allow you to define states and select against them using the `:state()` pseudo-class function.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The code below shows how this works using the example of an autonomous custom element that has an internal state `"collapsed"`.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The `collapsed` state is represented as a boolean property (with setter and getter methods) that is not visible outside of the element.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] To make this state selectable in CSS the custom element first calls `HTMLElement.attachInternals()` in its constructor in order to attach an `ElementInternals` object, which in turn provides access to a `CustomStateSet` through the `ElementInternals.states` property.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The setter for the (internal) collapsed state adds the *identifier* `hidden` to the `CustomStateSet` when the state is `true`, and removes it when the state is `false`.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The identifier is just a string: in this case we called it `hidden`, but we could have just as easily called it `collapsed`.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] We can use the identifier added to the custom element's `CustomStateSet` (`this._internals.states`) for matching the element's custom state.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] This is matched by passing the identifier to the `:state()` pseudo-class.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] For example, below we select on the `hidden` state being true (and hence the element's `collapsed` state) using the `:hidden` selector, and remove the border.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The `:state()` pseudo-class can also be used within the `:host()` pseudo-class function to match a custom state within a custom element's shadow DOM.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Additionally, the `:state()` pseudo-class can be used after the `::part()` pseudo-element to match the shadow parts of a custom element that is in a particular state.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] There are several live examples in `CustomStateSet` showing how this works.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] In the rest of this guide we'll look at a few example custom elements.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] You can find the source for all these examples, and more, in the web-components-examples repository, and you can see them all live at https://mdn.github.io/web-components-examples/.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] First, we'll look at an autonomous custom element.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The `<popup-info>` custom element takes an image icon and a text string as attributes, and embeds the icon into the page.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] When the icon is focused, it displays the text in a pop up information box to provide further in-context information.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] To begin with, the JavaScript file defines a class called `PopupInfo`, which extends the `HTMLElement` class.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The class definition contains the `constructor()` for the class, which always starts by calling `super()` so that the correct prototype chain is established.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Inside the method `connectedCallback()`, we define all the functionality the element will have when the element is connected to the DOM.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] In this case we attach a shadow root to the custom element, use some DOM manipulation to create the element's internal shadow DOM structure — which is then attached to the shadow root — and finally attach some CSS to the shadow root to style it.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] We don't do this work in the constructor because an element's attributes are unavailable until it is connected to the DOM.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] In the above example we apply styles to the shadow DOM using a `<style>` element, but you can reference an external stylesheet from a `<link>` element instead.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] In this example we'll modify the `<popup-info>` custom element to use an external stylesheet.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] It's just like the original `<popup-info>` example, except that we link to an external stylesheet using a `<link>` element, which we add to the shadow DOM.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Note that `<link>` elements do not block paint of the shadow root, so there may be a flash of unstyled content (FOUC) while the stylesheet loads.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Many modern browsers implement an optimization for `<style>` tags either cloned from a common node or that have identical text, to allow them to share a single backing stylesheet.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] With this optimization the performance of external and internal styles should be similar.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Now let's have a look at a customized built in element example.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] This example extends the built-in `<ul>` element to support expanding and collapsing the list items.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Note that this time we extend `HTMLUListElement`, rather than `HTMLElement`.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] This means that we get the default behavior of a list, and only have to implement our own customizations.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] As before, most of the code is in the `connectedCallback()` lifecycle callback.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] You use a `<ul>` element as normal, but specify the name of the custom element inside the `is` attribute.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] So far we've seen only one lifecycle callback in action: `connectedCallback()`.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] In the final example, `<custom-square>`, we'll see some of the others.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The `<custom-square>` autonomous custom element draws a square whose size and color are determined by two attributes, named `"size"` and `"color"`.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The key function in this example is `updateStyle()` — this takes an element, gets its shadow root, finds its `<style>` element, and adds `width`, `height`, and `background-color` to the style.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The actual updates are all handled by the lifecycle callbacks.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] The `attributeChangedCallback()` callback is run whenever one of the element's attributes is changed in some way.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] As you can see from its parameters, it is possible to act on attributes individually, looking at their name, and old and new attribute values.
[src:web-components/using-custom-elements] Note that to get the `attributeChangedCallback()` callback to fire when an attribute changes, you have to observe the attributes.
[src:web-components/web-components] There are two parts to Custom Elements: autonomous custom elements and customized built-in elements.
[src:web-components/web-components] Autonomous custom elements are HTML elements that are entirely separated from native HTML elements; they are essentially built from the bottom up using the Custom Elements API.
[src:web-components/web-components] Customized built-in elements are elements that are built upon native HTML elements to reuse their functionality.
[src:web-components/web-components] The Shadow DOM is a functionality that allows the web browser to render DOM elements without putting them into the main document DOM tree.
[src:web-components/web-components] This creates a barrier between what the developer and the browser can reach; the developer cannot access the Shadow DOM in the same way they would with nested elements, while the browser can render and modify that code the same way it would with nested elements.
[src:web-components/web-components] The impact of CSS scoped within the Shadow DOM of a particular element is that HTML elements can be encapsulated without the risk of CSS styles leaking and affecting elements that they were not supposed to affect.
[src:web-components/web-components] Although these elements are encapsulated with regard to HTML and CSS, they can still fire events that can be picked up by other elements in the document.
[src:web-components/web-components] The scoped subtree in an element is called a shadow tree.
[src:web-components/web-components] The element the shadow tree is attached to is called a shadow host.
[src:web-components/web-components] A Shadow DOM must always be connected to an existing element, either through attaching it as a literal element or through scripting.
[src:web-components/web-components] In JavaScript, Shadow DOMs are attached to an element using `Element.attachShadow()`.
[src:web-components/web-components] An HTML template defines a block of HTML content that is not rendered when the page loads, but can be instantiated during runtime.
[src:web-components/web-components] Scripts within a template do not run, and resources are not fetched, until the content is cloned or added to the DOM.
[src:web-components/web-components] Web Components are supported by current versions of all major browsers.
[src:web-components/web-components] Backward compatibility with older browsers is implemented using JavaScript-based polyfills.
[src:web-components/web-components] There are many libraries that are built on Web Components with the aim of increasing the level of abstraction when creating custom elements.
[src:web-components/web-components] There are numerous community efforts for the Web Components ecosystem.
[src:web-components/web-components] WebComponents.org provides an interface to search for any existing Web Components.
[src:web-components/web-components] Custom Elements Everywhere validates whether popular front-end frameworks are compatible and ready to use Web Components standard, with a set of pending bugs and available workarounds.
[src:web-components/web-components] Moreover, Vaadin Tutorials has a dedicated section that shows how those workarounds are used efficiently with example demo apps and similarly related topics.
[src:web-components/web-components] In 2011, Web Components were introduced for the first time by Alex Russell at Fronteers Conference.
[src:web-components/web-components] In 2013, Polymer, a library based on Web Components was released by Google.
[src:web-components/web-components] Polymer is canonical implementation of Material Design for web application user interfaces.
[src:web-components/web-components] In 2016, RequireJS was introduced as JavaScript library and AMD loader plugin for custom elements.
[src:web-components/web-components] In 2017, Ionic (mobile app framework) team built StencilJS, a JavaScript compiler that generates Web Components.
[src:web-components/web-components] In 2018, Angular 6 introduced Angular Elements that lets you package your Angular components as custom web elements, which are part of the web components set of web platform APIs.
[src:web-components/web-components] In 2018, Firefox 63 enabled Web Components support by default and updated the developer tools to support them.
[src:web-components/web-components] In 2018, LitElement was developed by the Google Chrome team as part of larger Polymer project.
[src:web-components/web-components] LitElement was designed to be a lightweight and easy-to-use framework for creating web components.
